8 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
9 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
10 Article – Family Law
11 5–701.
12 (a) Except as otherwise provided in § 5–705.1 of this subtitle, in this subtitle the
13 following words have the meanings indicated.
14 (b) (1) “Abuse” means:
15 (i) the physical or mental injury of a child under circumstances that
16 indicate that the child’s health or welfare is harmed or at substantial risk of being harmed
17 by:
18 1. a parent;
19 2. a household member or family member;
20 3. a person who has permanent or temporary care or custody
21 of the child;
22 4. a person who has responsibility for supervision of the
23 child; or
24 5. a person who, because of the person’s position or
25 occupation, exercises authority over the child;
26 (ii) sexual abuse of a child, whether physical injuries are sustained
27 or not; or
28 (iii) labor trafficking of a child by any individual.
29 (2) “ABUSE” INCLUDES FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION, AS DEFINED
30 IN § 20–601 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.

SENATE BILL 907 3
1 (3) “Abuse” does not include the physical injury of a child by accidental
2 means.
3 5–704.
4 (a) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, including any law on privileged
5 communications, each health practitioner, police officer, educator, or human service
6 worker, acting in a professional capacity in this State who has reason to believe that a child
7 has been subjected to abuse or neglect:
8 (1) shall notify the local department or the appropriate law enforcement
9 agency; and
10 (2) if acting as a staff member of a hospital, public health agency, child care
11 institution, juvenile detention center, school, or similar institution, shall immediately
12 notify and give all information required by this section to the head of the institution or the
13 designee of the head.
14 (b) (1) An individual who notifies the appropriate authorities under subsection
15 (a) of this section shall make:
16 (i) an oral report, by telephone or direct communication, as soon as
17 possible to the local department or appropriate law enforcement agency; and
18 (ii) a written report:
19 1. to the local department not later than 48 hours after the
20 contact, examination, attention, or treatment that caused the individual to believe that the
21 child had been subjected to abuse or neglect; and
22 2. with a copy to the local State’s Attorney.
23 (2) (i) An agency to which an oral report of suspected abuse or neglect
24 is made under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall immediately notify the other agency.
25 (ii) This paragraph does not prohibit a local department and an
26 appropriate law enforcement agency from agreeing to cooperative arrangements.
27 (c) Insofar as is reasonably possible, an individual who makes a report under this
28 section shall include in the report the following information:
29 (1) the name, age, and home address of the child;
30 (2) the name and home address of the child’s parent or other person who is
31 responsible for the child’s care;
32 (3) the whereabouts of the child;

4 SENATE BILL 907
1 (4) the nature and extent of the abuse or neglect of the child, including any
2 evidence or information available to the reporter concerning possible previous instances of
3 abuse or neglect; and
4 (5) any other information that would help to determine:
5 (i) the cause of the suspected abuse or neglect; and
6 (ii) the identity of any individual responsible for the abuse or neglect.
7 Article – Health – General
8 20–601.
9 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION” MEANS A PROCEDURE
10 PERFORMED FOR NONMEDICAL REASONS THAT INVOLVES PARTIAL OR TOTAL
11 REMOVAL OF OR OTHER INJURY TO THE EXTERNAL FEMALE GENITALIA, INCLUDING:
12 (1) A CLITORIDECTOMY OR THE PARTIAL OR TOTAL REMOVAL OF THE
13 CLITORIS, PREPUCE, OR CLITORAL HOOD;
14 (2) EXCISION OR THE PARTIAL OR TOTAL REMOVAL, WITH OR
15 WITHOUT EXCISION OF THE CLITORIS, OF THE LABIA MINORA, WITH OR WITHOUT
16 REMOVAL OF THE LABIA MAJORA;
17 (3) INFIBULATION OR THE NARROWING OF THE VAGINAL OPENING,
18 WITH OR WITHOUT EXCISION OF THE CLITORIS; OR
19 (4) ANY OTHER PROCEDURE THAT IS HARMFUL TO THE EXTERNAL
20 FEMALE GENITALIA, INCLUDING PRICKING, PIERCING, INCISING, SCRAPING, OR
21 CAUTERIZING THE GENITAL AREA.
22 [20–601.] 20–602.
23 (a) Except as provided in [§ 20–602] § 20–603 of this subtitle, a person [who
24 circumcises, excises, or infibulates the whole or any part of the labia majora or labia minora
25 or clitoris of an individual who is under the age of 18 years is guilty of] MAY NOT:
26 (1) KNOWINGLY PERFORM, ATTEMPT TO PERFORM, OR CONSPIRE TO
27 PERFORM female genital mutilation ON AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS UNDER THE AGE OF 18
28 YEARS; OR

SENATE BILL 907 5
1 (2) TRANSPORT AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS UNDER THE AGE OF 18 YEARS
2 OUT OF THE STATE FOR THE PURPOSE OF PERFORMING OR FACILITATING THE
3 PERFORMANCE OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION ON THE INDIVIDUAL.
4 (b) Except as provided in [§ 20–602] § 20–603 of this subtitle, a parent, guardian,
5 or other individual is guilty of female genital mutilation if the individual:
6 (1) Is legally responsible and charged with the care or custody of a child
7 under the age of 18 years; and
8 (2) Knowingly consents to [the circumcision, excision, or infibulation of the
9 whole or any part of the labia majora or labia minora or clitoris of] THE PERFORMANCE
10 OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION ON the child.
11 [20–602.] 20–603.
12 (a) A surgical operation is not a violation of this subtitle if the operation is
13 necessary to the health of the individual on whom it is performed and is performed by a
14 person licensed in the State as a medical practitioner.
15 (b) In determining whether an operation is necessary to the health of the
16 individual, no account may be taken of the belief on the part of any individual that the
17 operation is required as a matter of custom or ritual.
18 [20–603.] 20–604.
19 (A) A person who violates the provisions of this subtitle is guilty of a felony and
20 on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding [5] 10 years or a fine not exceeding
21 [$5,000] $10,000 or both.
22 (B) IF AN INDIVIDUAL WHO HOLDS A LICENSE ISSUED UNDER THE HEALTH
23 OCCUPATIONS ARTICLE IS CONVICTED OF, ENTERS A PLEA OF GUILTY OR OF NOLO
24 CONTENDERE FOR, OR RECEIVES PROBATION BEFORE JUDGMENT FOR A VIOLATION
25 OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE APPLICABLE HEALTH OCCUPATIONS BOARD SHALL REVOKE
26 THE LICENSE OF THE INDIVIDUAL.
27 20–605.
28 (A) A VICTIM OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION PERFORMED IN VIOLATION
29 OF THIS SUBTITLE MAY FILE AN ACTION IN THE CIRCUIT COURT IN THE COUNTY IN
30 WHICH THE VIOLATION OCCURRED OR THE VICTIM RESIDES.
31 (B) IF THE COURT FINDS THAT A PERSON VIOLATED THIS SUBTITLE, THE
32 COURT MAY AWARD THE PLAINTIFF:

6 SENATE BILL 907
1 (1) ACTUAL DAMAGES;
2 (2) COMPENSATORY DAMAGES;
3 (3) PUNITIVE DAMAGES;
4 (4) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES, COURT COSTS, AND LITIGATION
5 EXPENSES, INCLUDING EXPERT WITNESS FEES AND EXPENSES; AND
6 (5) ANY OTHER APPROPRIATE RELIEF.
7 (C) AN ACTION BROUGHT UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION SHALL
8 BE FILED THE LATER OF:
9 (1) NOT MORE THAN 10 YEARS AFTER THE DATE ON WHICH THE
10 VIOLATION OCCURRED; OR
11 (2) THE DATE ON WHICH THE VICTIM OF THE VIOLATION REACHES 28
12 YEARS OF AGE.
13 20–606.
14 (A) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2027, THE
15 DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE SOCIAL SERVICES ADMINISTRATION,
16 STATE AND LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES, AND OTHER APPROPRIATE
17 GOVERNMENT AGENCIES AND PUBLIC AND PRIVATE ORGANIZATIONS, SHALL
18 SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF
19 THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, CONTAINING DE–IDENTIFIED AND
20 DISAGGREGATED DATA ON THE NUMBER OF:
21 (1) REPORTS OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION SUBMITTED IN
22 ACCORDANCE WITH § 5–704 OF THE FAMILY LAW ARTICLE;
23 (2) INDIVIDUALS PROSECUTED FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS SUBTITLE;
24 (3) INDIVIDUALS CONVICTED OF A VIOLATION OF THIS SUBTITLE;
25 (4) CIVIL ACTIONS FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SUBTITLE; AND
26 (5) CIVIL ACTIONS UNDER THIS SUBTITLE IN WHICH A JUDGMENT
27 WAS ENTERED, WHETHER BY SETTLEMENT OR ADJUDICATION.

SENATE BILL 907 7
1 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL MAKE THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER
2 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION AVAILABLE TO THE PUBLIC.
3 20–607.
4 THE DEPARTMENT, IN COLLABORATION WITH COMMUNITY–BASED
5 ORGANIZATIONS, SHALL:
6 (1) DEVELOP AND PUBLISH CULTURALLY AND LINGUISTICALLY
7 APPROPRIATE EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS ON FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION,
8 INCLUDING:
9 (I) THE SIGNS THAT AN INDIVIDUAL HAS BEEN SUBJECTED TO
10 FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION;
11 (II) THE PHYSICAL AND MENTAL HEALTH RISKS CAUSED BY
12 FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION; AND
13 (III) THE CRIMINAL PENALTIES FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS
14 SUBTITLE; AND
15 (2) DISTRIBUTE THE EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS DESCRIBED UNDER
16 ITEM (1) OF THIS SECTION TO:
17 (I) HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS;
18 (II) LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES;
19 (III) SCHOOLS;
20 (IV) THE PUBLIC; AND
21 (V) ANY OTHER PROFESSIONAL OR COMMUNITY–BASED
22 ORGANIZATIONS THAT MAY WORK OR INTERACT WITH INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE AT
23 RISK OF FEMALE GENITAL MUTILATION.
24 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
25 October 1, 2026.

